data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

**What happened:** In C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (span-based) instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

**How to fix — cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>`:**

```csharp
// Before (breaks in .NET 10 / C# 14)
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.Contains(num);

// After — force Enumerable.Contains resolution
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Or use an explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches force the compiler to pick `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`, which is representable in an expression tree.
